<h2>Why Solana Benefits Most from the EO</h2>





<p>While the EO is blockchain-agnostic in theory, <strong>Solana is disproportionately positioned to benefit</strong> for several structural reasons:</p>





<h3>1. Speed and Throughput</h3>


<p>The Treasury Department's mandate to explore public blockchain infrastructure specifically requires networks capable of handling <strong>enterprise-grade transaction volumes</strong>. Solana's 65,000 TPS capacity - compared to Ethereum's ~15 TPS on L1 - makes it the only major L1 blockchain that can scale to national payment system requirements without L2 workarounds.</p>





<h3>2. Low Transaction Costs</h3>


<p>Bank integration requires microtransaction feasibility. Solana's sub-cent fees make it viable for high-frequency, low-value transactions that are the backbone of traditional banking. On Ethereum, a single swap can cost $5-50 during congestion - impractical for everyday banking use.</p>





<h3>3. Existing DeFi Infrastructure</h3>


<p>Solana already hosts the most liquid on-chain order book markets (via Jupiter DEX aggregator), the largest lending protocols outside Ethereum (Kamino, Marginfi), and the most advanced liquid staking ecosystem (Marinade, Jito). Banks looking to integrate crypto will likely start with established, audited protocols.</p>





<h3>4. Meme Coin Trading Volume</h3>


<p>Solana processes over 70% of all meme coin trading volume globally. With banks now able to offer crypto trading, Solana-based tokens - including <strong>DogeKing ($DKING)</strong>, Bonk, and other community tokens - become accessible to millions of mainstream banking customers for the first time.</p>





<div class="warning-box">


  <strong>âÅ¡ ïÂ¸Â Near-Term Caution:</strong> While the long-term outlook is bullish, the 90-day implementation window means nothing changes overnight. Banks need time to build compliant infrastructure. Expect the first bank crypto products to launch in Q3-Q4 2026.


</div>





